90–Male":"1390–Zesnulý","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1346–Male":"1346–Zesnulý","1358–1390":"1358–1390","about 1392":"okolo 1392","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1422":"1422","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Giddecote, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1372–1392":"1372–1392","1380–Male":"1380–Afdød","1382–Male":"1382–Afdød","1390–Male":"1390–Afdød","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1346–Male":"1346–Afdød","1358–1390":"1358–1390","about 1392":"omkring 1392","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1422":"1422","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Giddecote, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1372–1392":"1372–1392","1380–Male":"1380–Overleden","1382–Male":"1382–Overleden","1390–Male":"1390–Overleden","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1346–Male":"1346–Overleden","1358–1390":"1358–1390","about 1392":"circa 1392","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1422":"1422","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Giddecote, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1372–1392":"1372–1392","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1382–Male":"1382–Deceased","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1346–Male":"1346–Deceased","1358–1390":"1358–1390","about 1392":"about 1392","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1422":"1422","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Giddecote, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dennis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Denis(e)</i>, <i>Dinis(e)</i>, vernacular forms of Latin <i>Dionysius</i>, Greek <i>Dionysios</i> ‘(follower) of <i>Dionysos</i>’, an eastern god introduced to the classical pantheon at a relatively late date and bearing a name of probably Semitic origin. The name was borne by various early Christian saints, including Saint Denis, the martyred 3rd-century bishop of Paris who became the patron saint of France. From the 12th century onward, the popularity of the name in England (and of its cognates, mainly   Denis  , in the continental Europe) seems to have been largely due to French influence. The feminine form <i>Dionysia</i> (in vernacular English likewise <i>Den(n)is</i>) is also found, and some examples of the surname may originate from it.","English: from Middle English <i>deneis</i>, a variant of <i>danais</i> ‘Danish’, with the vowel influenced by Middle English <i>denshe</i> (Old English <i>denisc</i>). Compare   Dence  .","Irish (mainly Dublin and Cork): of the same origin as 1 and 2 above, sometimes an alternative form to   Donohue   but more often to   McDonough  , since the personal name <i>Donnchadh</i> was Anglicized as <i>Donough</i> or <i>Denis</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Dec","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Aleksander, Andrzej, Casimir, Ignacy, Jerzy, Krystyna, Krzysztof, Malgorzata, Mikolaj, Stanislaw, Tadeusz.","Polish: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Dionizy</i>, Polish form of <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  )."]},{"name":"Dennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ) + <i>-son</i>. Compare   Tennyson  .","English (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>deinzein</i>, a burgess who enjoyed the privileges of those living <i>deinz la cité</i> ‘within the city’."]},{"name":"Denny","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>Den(n)y</i>, a pet form of the personal name <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Tenney  .","English: habitational name from Danny in Hurstpierpoint, Sussex, recorded as <i>Danye</i> in 1343. Alternatively, the name may arise from Denny in Waterbeach, Cambridgeshire, but no medieval evidence with a habitative preposition has been found in the case of the latter.","Scottish: habitational name from Denny in Stirlingshire."]},{"name":"Diniz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Augusto, Celso, Francisco, Luis, Ricardo, Rogerio, Alvaro, Anselmo, Antero, Carlos.  Portuguese Joao, Marcio.","Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Dinis</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  )."]},{"name":"Denes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Bela, Laszlo, Miklos, Tibor, Aranka, Balint, Endre, Ferenc, Lajos, Zoltan.  Jewish Imrich, Meyer.  Romanian Doina, Matei, Radu.","Hungarian (<b>Dénes</b>): from the personal name <i>Dénes</i>, from Greek <i>Dionysios</i> (see   Dennis  ). The surname <i>Dénes</i> is also found in Slovakia; compare 2 below.","Slovak (<b>Deneš</b> and <b>Déneš</b>) and Romanian (also <b>Deneş</b>): from the Hungarian personal name <i>Dénes</i> ‘Dennis’, or an adaptation of the Hungarian surname <b>Dénes</b> (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Dennett","meanings":["English: from a pet form of Middle English <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ), or possibly from a pet form of <i>Denise</i>, as, for example, <i>Denote</i>, a female character in <i>Piers Plowman</i>."]},{"name":"Dinges","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dings  ."]},{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Dings","meanings":["Dutch and German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dinges  ."]},{"name":"Dinis","meanings":["Portuguese and Galician: from <i>Dinis</i>, a Portuguese personal name equivalent to   Dennis  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Dennis Esq. was born in 1372, his father, Walter Dennis, was 27 and his mother, Maud Bockerel, was 15. He married Margaret Corbett about 1392, in Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1392, in Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1372–1392":"1372–1392","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1382–Male":"1382–Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1358–1390":"1358–1390","about 1392":"umbes 1392","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1422":"1422","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Giddecote, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1372–1392":"1372–1392","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1382–Male":"1382–Kuollut","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","1358–1390":"1358–1390","about 1392":"noin 1392","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1422":"1422","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Giddecote, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1372–1392":"1372–1392","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1382–Male":"1382–Décédé","1390–Male":"1390–Décédé","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1346–Male":"1346–Décédé","1358–1390":"1358–1390","about 1392":"environ 1392","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1422":"1422","1376":"1376","1